data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration needed.** Your code uses only `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. The code will compile and run correctly as-is on `net8.0`.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort):

You could simplify with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`, but this is a stylistic improvement, not a migration requirement:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

Also note the classic closure-over-loop-variable bug: your `foreach` captures `item` by reference. On .NET Framework with C# < 5, all threads could see the *last* item. C# 5+ (which you'll use on .NET 8) fixed this, so it's safe — but worth being aware of.
